ion\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:343:\"Day in day out, we hear of some hacker taking down websites or launching Distributed Denial-of-Service (DDoS) attacks that result in making a website unavailable or unsafe for its users. An Unsafe website can contain viruses and malware, which infect its visitors or even gives the attacker full access over its database. If your website [...]\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Adriana Bantu\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5179:\"<p><img class=\"alignleft  wp-image-5290\" title=\"The Risks of an Unsafe Website\" src=\"http://www.websitedefender.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/unsafe-website-300x199.jpg\" alt=\"What is an Unsafe Website\" width=\"243\" height=\"161\" />Day in day out, we hear of some hacker taking down websites or launching Distributed Denial-of-Service (DDoS) attacks that result in making a website unavailable or unsafe for its users. An Unsafe website can contain viruses and malware, which infect its visitors or even gives the attacker full access over its database. If your website is compromised, your customers’ personal and confidential information might be stolen, resulting in your website reaping negative publicity, pouring your reputation, which you had so meticulously built, down the drain. Besides that, web malware can also slow down your website, which will again drive customers or users away from your webpage. Google detects unsafe websites and place them on its infamous <a title=\"How to Get Removed from Google Blacklist\" href=\"http://www.websitedefender.com/web-security/get-removed-from-google-blacklist/\">Google Blacklist</a> in order to protect the visitors.</p>\n<p>An unsafe website is exposed to a number of <a title=\"Web Vulnerabilities, Threats and Risks\" href=\"http://www.websitedefender.com/web-security/web-security-tip-of-the-week-web-vulnerabilities-threats-risks/\">web vulnerabilities, threats and risks</a> that can effectively compromise it. Here are some dangerous threats you should consider:</p>\n<h2>Maladvertising and Fake ads</h2>\n<p>Cybercriminals use various approaches to exploit online ads and to use them for spreading malware. Some hackers breach into unprotected online advertising networks and compromise legitimate ads. Others use fake ads with fictitious fronts acting as authentic and harmless ads. These ads can hide malicious codes and JavaScript, which limit your control and make your website unsafe for your visitors. It is likely that they also contain <a title=\"What are Trojans\" href=\"http://www.websitedefender.com/what-is-malware/#trojans\">Trojans</a>, viruses and other parasites, which steal information from the user’s browser. If you don&#8217;t have the means to check the security of the ads you place on your website, important customers might stop doing business with you once their devices are affected.</p>\n<h2>Fake Warnings</h2>\n<p>Hackers can inject malicious code into your website and redirect your visitors to another URL that displays fake malware/spyware warning messages and promote some form of antivirus solution. However, these messages actually hide Trojans and viruses and usually read something like the following:</p>\n<p><em>“System Alert! Your computer is infected!</em><br />\n<em> Windows had detected spyware infection!</em><br />\n<em> It is recommended to use special antispyware tools to prevent data loss. Windows will now download and install the most up-to-date antispyware for you.</em><br />\n<em> Click here to protect your computer from spyware.”</em></p>\n<p>As soon as your users see the malware warning message and click on the download button, the virus or Trojan downloads itself into your users’ devices.</p>\n<h2>Outdated Themes and Plugins</h2>\n<p>Un-updated versions of installed themes and plugins pose another security risk to your website. New updates for the installed theme and plugins address security issues and bugs reported in earlier versions. If you don’t update to the latest version, then you have an unsafe website, exposed to hackers who can simply exploit the weak spots reported in the earlier version.</p>\n<h2><strong>Safeguard your Website with WebsiteDefender</strong></h2>\n<p>Certain specialized security services like WebsiteDefender can help you ensure that you have a <a title=\"What a Clean Website Means\" href=\"http://www.websitedefender.com/web-security/monitor-clean-website/\">clean website</a>. WebsiteDefender is an online <a title=\"Why You Need a Website Monitor\" href=\"http://www.websitedefender.com/web-security/why-website-monitor/\">website monitor</a> packed with a complete set of security features which include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Checking your website regularly for vulnerabilities, malware and hacker activity.</li>\n<li>Alerting if your installed themes and plugins are updated or insecure.</li>\n<li>Ensuring that your website files and database are safely backed up and stored. In case your website is compromised, you can easily restore your entire website including WordPress databases, plugins and themes.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><a title=\"WebsiteDefender Registration Page\" href=\"https://dashboard.websitedefender.com/register-for-free-website-scan.php\">Sign up for a WebsiteDefender account</a> to detect malicious ads or code injected on your website early.</p>\n<p>&#8216;Like&#8217; the <a title=\"WebsiteDefender Facebook Page\" href=\"http://www.facebook.com/WebsiteDefender\" target=\"_blank\">WebsiteDefender Facebook page</a> and read the <a title=\"WebsiteDefender Security Blog\" href=\"http://www.websitedefender.com/blog/\">WebsiteDefender Blog </a> to keep up-to-date with the latest security news.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:64:\"http://www.websitedefender.com/web-security/unsafe-website/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:56:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n			\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:90:\"Web Security Tip of the Week: How Often Should You Check for Web Security Vulnerabilities?\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:73:\"http://www.websitedefender.com/web-security/web-security-vulnerabilities/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:82:\"http://www.websitedefender.com/web-security/web-security-vulnerabilities/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Tue, 15 May 2012 13:36:22 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:6:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Security Tips\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;